# AuraScan â€” AI Facial Analysis

## Project identity
- Product: AuraScan â€” AI facial analysis for aesthetic insights
- Stack: Next.js 15 (App Router), Python FastAPI, MongoDB, MediaPipe, OpenCV, OpenAI
- Client: Jay Michaels (Crest Infosystems proposal, July 2026)

## Non-negotiable: Math engine vs AI
- MediaPipe (478 landmarks) + OpenCV produce ALL measurements, scores, and ratios.
- OpenAI MUST NOT replace, override, or invent numerical facial metrics.
- OpenAI is allowed ONLY for: narrative explanations, recommendations, protocols, chat, and image generation (visual features).
- Store deterministic `cvReport` and landmarks in MongoDB before any OpenAI enrichment.
- AI text must reference stored metrics; never hallucinate measurements.

## Architecture rules
- Next.js: UI, routing, auth session, API calls. No business logic duplication of CV math.
- Python FastAPI: image processing, MediaPipe, cv_report building, PDF, webhooks, OpenAI server-side calls.
- MongoDB: primary store for users, assessments, analysis JSON, report status, payments, conversations.
- Use environment variables for secrets; never commit API keys.

## Next.js conventions
- App Router only (`app/`). Client components marked `'use client'`.
- Fetch backend via env `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL` (never hardcode localhost in production).
- Prefer server actions or API routes only as BFF proxies when needed; heavy work stays in Python.
- Tailwind for styling; match existing AuraScan design tokens (brand teal, Sora/Inter).

## Python conventions
- FastAPI routers per domain: `auth`, `assessments`, `analysis`, `reports`, `admin`, `payments`, `ai`.
- Pydantic models for request/response; validate all inputs.
- Reuse existing modules: `mediapipe_analysis.py`, `cv_report.py`, `opencv_metrics.py`.
- Async where I/O-bound; keep MediaPipe on thread pool if blocking.

## MongoDB conventions
- Use Motor (async) or PyMongo with clear repository layer â€” no raw queries in route handlers.
- Store full MediaPipe landmark arrays and `cvReport` as BSON documents.
- Index: `users.email`, `reports.userId + status`, `assessments.createdAt`.
- Report status enum: `draft` | `pending_review` | `approved` | `published`.

## Report workflow
- Users cannot download PDF until status is `published` (or `approved` per product rule).
- Admin can edit AI narrative fields; cannot edit raw landmark/metric fields without re-analysis.
- Audit log admin actions on report state changes.

## Sprint discipline
- One sprint at a time. User must say "go" before starting next sprint.
- Each sprint ends with: working demo, test checklist, no broken existing features.
- Minimize scope; no bonus features unless requested.
- Develop and verify features locally first; final deployment/handover should happen near the end unless a sprint explicitly requires environment readiness.

## Code quality
- Small, reviewable PRs. Match existing naming and file structure.
- No over-engineering. No new dependencies without justification.
- Comments only for non-obvious business logic.

## Deployment
- Client deployment target: Replit, per proposal/client direction.
- MongoDB Atlas remains the primary database.
- Sprint 3 should prepare Replit compatibility and runbook only; do not spend the next feature sprints on final deployment unless the user explicitly asks.
- Final Replit deployment, end-to-end testing, optimization, and handover belong near the final sprint after core features are complete.
- Local development remains the default working mode during feature sprints.

## Forbidden
- Replacing MediaPipe measurements with LLM estimates
- Storing passwords in plain text
- Committing `.env`, `venv/`, `.next/`
- Building multiple milestones in one sprint without approval
